        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  Define the CellWithMeta schema — a Pydantic model for a single table cell containing text lines and HTML-like cell properties (colspan, rowspan). </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Table cell data model for document tables. \par \b Input\/ \:  None (standalone model, references LineWithMeta). \par \b Output\/ \:  Pydantic BaseModel <computeroutput>CellWithMeta</computeroutput> with lines, colspan, rowspan, invisible fields. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(7): pydantic.BaseModel; READS_DATA_FROM(8): LineWithMeta] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>colspan &gt;= 1, rowspan &gt;= 1.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>lines is never empty for visible cells (invisible=False). \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why model cells as having multiple LineWithMeta lines? A: A single table cell can contain multiple lines of text with individual annotations, mirroring real document structure. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 – Initial creation with semantic markup] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 9[Table cell with text lines and span attributes] =&gt; CellWithMeta \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[CellWithMeta]: TableRenderer =&gt; IterateCells =&gt; RenderHTMLTableCell </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
